The '''Burdwood Bank''', called Namuncurá in [[Argentina]] and other countries, is an [[Ocean bank|undersea bank]] with a [[Topographic prominence|prominence]] of approximately {{Convert|200|m|fathom|abbr=on}}, part of the [[Scotia Arc]] projecting some {{Convert|600|km|abbr=on}} from [[Cape Horn]] in the [[South Atlantic Ocean]] and located some {{Convert|200|km|mi}} south of the [[Falkland Islands]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://geographic.org/geographic_names/name.php?uni=-236893&fid=6438&c=undersea_features |title = Burdwood Bank: Undersea Features |work = Geographical Names |publisher = [[National Geospatial‐Intelligence Agency]] |location = Bethesda, Maryland |accessdate = 9 June 2013}}</ref> Argentina claims economic rights over the whole of the bank, while the United Kingdom has designated about half of the bank as part of the Falklands Outer Economic Zone.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/ibru/south_atlantic_maritime_claims.pdf |title = Claims and potential claims to maritime jurisdiction in the South Atlantic and Southern Oceans by Argentina and the UK |publisher = International Boundaries Research Unit, [[Durham University]] |accessdate = 11 June 2013 |date = 24 June 2010}}</ref>
The Burdwood Bank is one of the four morphological features defined by the 200&nbsp;m isobath off the coast of the Argentine&nbsp;— the other three being the [[Patagonian Shelf]] (Argentine Coastal Shelf), [[Isla de los Estados]] and the Falkland Islands. It forms a barrier to the northward flow of the [[Antarctic Circumpolar Current]]. The Bank itself (as defined by the 200&nbsp;m isobath) is some {{Convert|300|km|abbr=on}} from east to west and some {{Convert|60|km|abbr=on}} from north to south. The channel to the west of the bank is about {{Convert|80|km|abbr=on}} wide and {{Convert|400|m|fathom|abbr=on}} deep while the channel to the east of the bank is {{Convert|130|km|abbr=on}} wide and has a depth of up to {{Convert|1800|m|fathom|abbr=on}} deep.<ref>{{cite journal |journal = INIDEP Documento Cientifico|volume = 5|id = INIDEP Contribution Nº 1083 |url = http://www.oceandocs.org/bitstream/1834/2575/1/INIDEP%20Doc.%20Cient.%205%207-22.pdf |title = Oceanographic Conditions at the Southern End of the Argentine Continental Slope |last1 = Guerrero|first1 = Raúl |first2 = Ana|last2 = Baldoni |first3 = Hugo|last3 = Benavides |publisher = National Institute for Fisheries Research and Development (INIDEP) |location = [[Mar del Plata]], Argentina|year = 1999|accessdate = 9 June 2013|pages = 7–22}}</ref>
