{{Politics of Northern Cyprus}}

The '''Populist Party''' ({{lang-tr|Halkçı Parti}}) was a left-wing political party in [[Northern Cyprus]] between 1975 and 1981.

==History==
The party was established in 1975 by [[Alper Orhon]], and won two seats in the [[Northern Cyprus parliamentary election, 1976|1976 elections]].<ref name=VM>Vincent E McHale (1983) ''Political parties of Europe'', Greenwood Press, p122 {{ISBN|0-313-23804-9}}</ref> However, the following year one of its two MPs defected to the [[Communal Liberation Party]]. In 1981 it merged into the [[Democratic People's Party (Northern Cyprus)|Democratic People's Party]].<ref name=VM/>

==Ideology==
The party had [[social democratic]] principles, and was considered to be a Cypriot version of the [[Republican People's Party (Turkey)|Republican People's Party]] in Turkey.<ref name=VM/> It was critical of the [[National Unity Party (Northern Cyprus)|National Unity Party]] government's handling of economic affairs, particularly the dependence on Turkey for economic development. It supported government-run enterprises and the participation of workers in planning.<ref>McHale, p123</ref>

